That brings us to verse 31 where Jesus talks about divorce

Let's read verses 31 and 32 and then unpack marriage and divorce to dissect what Jesus is saying here

--> Read verses 31-32

In order to really understand what Jesus is saying here, we need to understand why he's saying it and that requires us to understand the state of things in the first century when this was written

At the time, the standard for divorce was very low. So low that practically speaking, a husband could divorce his wife for just about anything

If she burnt the dinner bread, a man could divorce his wife

In Deuteronomy 24, God seems to allow for divorce on the grounds of a man finding something indecent about his wife

Jesus later qualifies this statement in Matthew chapter 19 verse 8 by saying "Because of your hardness of heart Moses allowed you to divorce your wives, but from the beginning it was not so"

Jesus is saying that God did not intend for divorce to exist but due to the flaws, stubborness and cold hearts of men, divorce was permitted under certain circumstances

The certificate of divorce served as protection for women because it gave them legal standing to remarry. This way a man couldn't just separate from his wife without official documentation

At the time, the religious leaders in Isreal would likely allow men to divorce their wives for nonsensical reasons

Jesus opens these verses with the same "You were told this but im here to clarify" statement

What people were being told wasn't a complete reflection of Gods intent and so Jesus is going to clarify by giving a deeper explanation of Gods will and set a higher bar

Jesus is reminding people that God intended marriage to be for life

God didn't intend for marriages to be dissolved for petty reasons

Jesus is saying that divorce on any grounds other than sexual immorality is invalid

Because divorces done for any other reason than sexual immorality are invalid, men are effectively guilty of causing their wives to commit adultery when she remarries another man

In the same respect, any man who marries a woman who has been divorces for any reason other than sexual immorality is comitting adultery 

Through todays lens where divorce is normalized, those words by Jesus sound pretty intense

He really doesn't leave much room for confusion with those words. He's super clear and that can be hard for some to listen to who have experienced divorce

In Canada and the USA, the lifetime probability is that about 40% of marriages are expected to end in divorce

Today, divorce is basically viewed as the dissolution of a business arrangement, not as a breaking of a sacred covenant

I think that because divorce is so common today, it makes it a bit taboo to speak about the topic but I think it's an important one to discuss


To understand why Jesus is speaking about divorce, its helpful to understand God's original intent for marriage

Genesis chapter 2 verse 18 says:

"Then the Lord God said "it is not good that the man should be alone; I will make him a helper fit for him"

Chapter 2 verse 24 says:

Therefore a man shall leave his father and his mother and hold fast to his wife, and they shall become one flesh"

One flesh means two people are merging into one. It's permanent. Two lives become so intricately intertwined that separation is not possible

That's where the vow: till death do us part

God created marriage as a sacred covenant

Because men were flawed and because of the hardness of their hearts, divorce was created as a technicality to get out of honouring a sacred promise made before God to become one flesh

So while today divorce is treated as a business partnership dissolution, its more like cutting off the legs from your body. It should not be taken lightly.




Summary

At the time, people were getting divorced for frivolous reasons

Men were being told to simply give their wives a certificate of divorce and everything was fine

Jesus shows up and tell people that the only legitimate cause for divorce is sexual immorality. No other reason is legitimate and because of that mass adultery is being comitted

Jesus is clarifying his fathers intention and perspective on marriage. he's raising the bar for those who wish to follow him


